CREATED:20250920T163036Z
DESCRIPTION:<b>Re-Encuentros: Decolonial Dialogues on Latin America</b><br>
 A Hispanic Heritage Month Film &amp\; Lecture Series<br><br><u>About the Se
 ries</u><br>Join us for a celebration of Latin America's stories\, historie
 s\, and voices. Each Saturday evening features a powerful feature-length fi
 lm\, a short lecture from a graduate scholar or recent Ph.D. graduate\, and
  an open discussion where everyone is welcome to share their thoughts. This
  series embodies Re-encuentros (re- encounters) as a practice of reconnecti
 on and dialogue-to spark meaningful conversations about critical issues inv
 olving U.S.-Latin American relations\, colonial legacies\, and the struggle
 s and resilience of Latin American communities. Guided by the principles of
  decoloniality\, Re-encuentros creates a space to challenge harmful narrati
 ves\, uplift marginalized perspectives\, and celebrate cultural diversity. 
 Hosted in partnership with local venues\, the series brings scholarship and
  community together\, helping us forge new partnerships and spaces to engag
 e in critical dialogue and celebrate our diversity.<br><br><u>About the Fil
 m</u><br><i><br>Ixcanul </i>(2015)<p><i>Ixcanul</i> follows the story of Ma
 ría\, a 17-year-old Kaqchikel Mayan girl living with her family on a coffee
  plantation at the base of an active volcano in Guatemala. While her parent
 s have arranged for her to marry the farm's foreman\, María is drawn to a y
 oung man who dreams of escaping to the United States.</p><p>When her attemp
 t to get pregnant to run away with him backfires and she is left behind\, M
 aría's life takes a dramatic and tragic turn\, forcing her and her family i
 nto a devastating encounter with the modern world outside of their traditio
 nal community. The film highlights the exploitation and marginalization fac
 ed by indigenous people in Guatemala\, particularly due to cultural and lin
 guistic barriers.</p><p><u>Speaker &amp\; Talk</u></p><p>K. Ermelinda Garcí
 a is a Ph.D. candidate at Indiana University specializing in 20th Century M
 exico. Their research examines how women in the L(G)BT community in Mexico 
 City built organizing networks\, reimagined friendship and family\, and dis
 rupted established spaces throughout the latter 20th century and into the m
 odern day. Drawn to processes of construction and deconstruction\, Linda ex
 amines how sapphic and trans women's spaces were regularly re-imagined by t
 he very participants themselves. Women arriving to the city\, to newfound u
 nderstanding of themselves\, or to a greater calling. Their work seeks to a
 dd on to the political history by providing an insight into the emotional l
 ives of queer women.<u></u></p><p>Ixcanul (2015)\, written and directed by 
 Jayro Bustamante in his directorial debut\, takes place in a Maya village h
 oused on the flank of an active volcano. Centered on María and her family\,
  who live and work on a coffee plantation\, the film opens with an engageme
 nt ceremony between Maria and the plantation foreman Ignacio. Written in Fr
 ench but filmed completely in Kaqchikel and with a largely non-professional
  cast\, Bustamante sought to challenge its reputation as a low status langu
 age in Guatemala. Ixcanul\, through its narrative focus on María\, implores
  audiences to consider the multitude of factors which impact her present an
 d delineate the possibilities for her future. Exploring themes of gender\, 
 sexuality\, colonialism\, and the culture of mestizaje\, we invite you to c
 onsider the following questions. <i>Was Bustamante successful in what he so
 ught to convey? Does the language in which the source material was written 
 matter in telling a story? How does this film successfully-or not-set the s
 tage for a real discussion of the state of adoption in Guatemala?</i></p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20250920T231053Z
SEQUENCE:1
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Film Screening: Ixcanul (Re-Encuentros: Decolonial Dialogues on Lat
 in America)
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
