UID:2ll2k75ts1u6giou7mv65i5pk3@google.com
CREATED:20250402T153819Z
DESCRIPTION:<p>Please join us to celebrate the recent release of EdgarIllas
 ’s new book\, <i>The Magma of War: An Ontology of the Global</i> (Routledge
 \,2024). Edgar Illas is Professor in the Department of Spanish and Portugue
 se atIU\, specializing in Catalan culture\, political theory\, and theories
  of war. <i>TheMagma of War</i> develops a conceptual paradigm to understan
 d the centrality ofwar in producing social orders. At once deeply philosoph
 ical and concerned withconcrete contemporary political forms\, the book eng
 ages with theories of warfrom Heraclitus to Deleuze to explore how today’s 
 global order is paradoxicallyfounded on constant self-destruction. Edgar wi
 ll be in dialogue with AndrésGuzmán (Associate Prof.\, Spanish and Portugue
 se) before opening the discussion tothe audience. </p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20250404T122614Z
LOCATION:Redbud Books\, 408 W Kirkwood Ave\, Bloomington\, IN 47404\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Edgar Illas Book Launch: The Magma of War
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Redbud Books
DTSTART;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260130T170000
DTEND;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260130T190000
DTSTAMP:20260408T030320Z
UID:7h62h5l6ivjpvb2gq9ql7c437n@google.com
RECURRENCE-ID;TZID=America/Indiana/Indianapolis:20260130T180000
CREATED:20260121T165027Z
DESCRIPTION:<h2>The Dialectics of Technology and the Imperative of a Commun
 ist Scientific Program</h2><br>A talk by Sonali Gupta<p>This presentation o
 ffers a dialectical analysis of contemporary technological production\, arg
 uing that the catastrophic trajectories of computation\, artificial intelli
 gence\, biotechnology\, and geoengineering cannot be reduced to capitalism 
 alone\, but emerge from a dominant techne—a historically contingent mode of
  world-making that renders technological futures inevitable\, singular\, an
 d self-authorizing. We will explore how scientific methodologies\, metaphor
 s\, and regulatory regimes encode political and ontological commitments tha
 t reproduce domination even under ostensibly benevolent or anti-capitalist 
 aims. Through a methodological study of recent inflection points in technol
 ogical development\, I argue that transforming property relations is necess
 ary but insufficient to alter technological outcomes unless the productive 
 processes\, narratives\, and epistemologies of technological production the
 mselves are reconfigured. The paper advances the concept of a communist sci
 entific program—not as centralized expertise or state planning\, but as a d
 ialectical\, participatory\, and materially grounded practice capable of in
 terrupting technological inevitability\, preserving collective memory\, and
  cultivating alternative cosmotechnical horizons. By situating technology a
 s a site of struggle coextensive with politics and economics\, the paper co
 ntends that communism must become a world-building project at the level of 
 science and technics if it is to bifurcate the future and repair the metabo
 lic rift between life\, labor\, and the planet.</p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20260403T204234Z
LOCATION:Redbud Books\, 408 W Kirkwood Ave\, Bloomington\, IN 47404\, USA
SEQUENCE:1
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:ROSA Bloomington | Year 2 - Lecture
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE:Redbud Books
DTSTART:20250425T230000Z
DTEND:20250426T010000Z
DTSTAMP:20260408T030320Z
UID:3d0erc347pr4tj9ekisjp9r1mg@google.com
CREATED:20250108T035300Z
DESCRIPTION:<p>Experience the groundbreaking work of Barbara Hammer with a 
 special double feature: "Nitrate Kisses" (1992) and "No No Nooky TV" (1987)
 . "Nitrate Kisses" is a powerful documentary that intertwines archival foot
 age\, including scenes from the 1933 film "Lot in Sodom\," with contemporar
 y portrayals of lesbian and gay couples. It delves into the complexities of
  queer history\, highlighting the erasure of marginalized experiences and t
 he importance of reclaiming lost narratives. This cinematic experiment offe
 rs a candid and cutting-edge look into queer life and its subcultures.</p><
 p>Paired with this is the short film "No No Nooky TV\," a witty and experim
 ental exploration of romance and sexuality in the modern age. Using 16mm fi
 lm and Amiga computer techniques\, Hammer challenges conventional represent
 ations of love and desire\, offering a critical and humorous perspective. T
 his film playfully pokes fun at post-industrial romance and provides insigh
 tful observations on the differing perspectives of male and female sexualit
 y. Both films showcase Hammer's pioneering role in lesbian cinema\, address
 ing themes of queer representation and the reclaiming of marginalized histo
 ries.</p><br><i>Queer Underground</i><span> delves into the experimental\, 
 avant-garde\, and forgotten works of queer filmmakers\, showcasing the dive
 rse and often radical expressions of LGBTQ+ identity that have pushed bound
 aries and challenged conventions.</span>
LAST-MODIFIED:20250425T170226Z
LOCATION:Redbud Books\, 408 W Kirkwood Ave\, Bloomington\, IN 47404\, USA
SEQUENCE:1
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:(POSTPONED TO NEXT MONTH) Queer Underground Film Series: Nitrate Ki
 sses + No No Nooky TV
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
