UID:2iondmklntvh32m2478862ks1j@google.com
CREATED:20250920T231316Z
DESCRIPTION:<b>Re-Encuentros: Decolonial Dialogues on Latin America</b><br>
 A Hispanic Heritage Month Film &amp\; Lecture Series<br><br><u>About the Se
 ries</u><br>Join us for a celebration of Latin America's stories\, historie
 s\, and voices. Each Saturday evening features a powerful feature-length fi
 lm\, a short lecture from a graduate scholar or recent Ph.D. graduate\, and
  an open discussion where everyone is welcome to share their thoughts. This
  series embodies Re-encuentros (re- encounters) as a practice of reconnecti
 on and dialogue-to spark meaningful conversations about critical issues inv
 olving U.S.-Latin American relations\, colonial legacies\, and the struggle
 s and resilience of Latin American communities. Guided by the principles of
  decoloniality\, Re-encuentros creates a space to challenge harmful narrati
 ves\, uplift marginalized perspectives\, and celebrate cultural diversity. 
 Hosted in partnership with local venues\, the series brings scholarship and
  community together\, helping us forge new partnerships and spaces to engag
 e in critical dialogue and celebrate our diversity.<br><br><u>About the Fil
 m</u><br><i><br>And Starring Pancho Villa As Himself </i>(2003)<p><i>And St
 arring Pancho Villa as Himself</i> dramatizes a fascinating historical even
 t: the Mexican revolutionary Pancho Villa's decision to sell exclusive film
  rights to the American Mutual Film Corporation in 1914. Needing money to f
 und his war\, Villa allows a young American filmmaker\, Frank N. Thayer\, t
 o document his battles\, with the goal of improving his public image in the
  United States.</p><p>The movie follows the challenges faced by the film cr
 ew as they attempt to capture authentic combat footage while dealing with t
 he charismatic\, volatile\, and sometimes ruthless personality of Pancho Vi
 lla. It explores the blurred lines between historical fact and cinematic fi
 ction\, and the way filmmaking can be used as a powerful tool for propagand
 a and shaping public perception.</p><p><u>Speaker &amp\; Talk</u></p><p><br
 ></p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20251005T172724Z
LOCATION:Redbud Books\, 408 W Kirkwood Ave\, Bloomington\, IN 47404\, USA
SEQUENCE:0
STATUS:CONFIRMED
SUMMARY:Film Screening: And Starring Pancho Villa As Himself (Re-Encuentros
 : Decolonial Dialogues on Latin America)
TRANSP:OPAQUE
END:VEVENT
