CREATED:20250912T141357Z
DESCRIPTION:<p><b>IU Cultural Studies Program\, Culture Nights lecture seri
 es</b></p><p><b>The Crisis Machine: Border Logic and the Production of Perp
 etual Emergency<br></b>Aleshia Barajas\, Asst. Professor\, American Studies
 \, IU</p><p>September17\, 6pm @ Redbud Books<br>Free and open to the public
 </p><p>What if the US-Mexico border isn’t really about stopping migrants at
  all? The border operates as what I call a “crisis machine”—a self-replicat
 ing system that creates the very problems it claims to solve. From Chinese 
 immigrants in the1880s to Central American “gang-terrorists” today\, the bo
 rder consistently manufactures new enemy figures to justify its ongoing exp
 ansion. What started as a regional boundary now exports surveillance techno
 logies worldwide\, creating what journalist Todd Miller calls an “Empire of
  Borders.”</p><p>The experiences of legal border-crossers reveal something 
 unexpected: even students and workers who cross daily for school or jobs—th
 e most privileged travelers—describe the daily experience as “psychological
  torture” despite having proper documentation. Their stories illuminate how
  border logic works not through brute force but by making nation-state divi
 sions feel inevitable while rendering other ways of organizing human relati
 onships unthinkable.</p><p>This border logic extends far beyond the Rio Gra
 nde\, structuring how we understand citizenship\, security\, and human diff
 erence across American society. Crucially\, this logic shapes not just poli
 cy but cultural production\, identity formation\, and the very categories t
 hrough which we understand human difference and belonging. By examining how
  border communities navigate and sometimes resist these frameworks\, this w
 ork asks: what becomes possible when we recognize borders as powerful ideas
  rather than natural facts?</p>
LAST-MODIFIED:20250916T002756Z
